AB  - A new standard of lightweight, low cost, integrated GPS/INS products has been created with the introduction of Rockwell's family of MIGITS<sup>TM</sup> (Miniature Integrated GPS/INS Tactical System) products. This family takes full advantage of the precision pseudorange and pseudorange rate information available only from an embedded GPS receiver. This information is integrated with inertial data in a single Kalman filter in a synergistic manner which results in superior operation in high dynamic, antenna shading, and jamming environments. As this paper will show, the Rockwell MIGITS has successfully demonstrated ability to tightly couple a tactical grade IMU with GPS to provide precise navigation operation in a dynamic environment. As the primary supplier of GPS user equipment to the military, Rockwell International has played a pioneering role in the development and success of GPS. The introduction of the integrated GPS/INS system advances the evolution of strapdown inertial systems and stand-alone GPS receivers that began over 20 years ago. Rockwell's Collins Avionics & Communications Division (CACD) established itself in the pursuit of integrated systems with leadership in the development of both stand-alone and integrated GPS systems during the technology's infancy in the early seventies, and has continued to help advance the state of the art to where it is today. GPS receivers have continued to advance largely through a decrease in size as well as improved performance in a variety of environments such as jamming. The integrated systems described in this paper build upon the lessons learned and the continued evolution of GPS. Continual refinements in research and development programs at Rockwell have led to this family of small integrated systems, resulting in what we believe is the world's smallest, integrated GPS/INS systems available today, the MIGITS. The MIGITS products are intended to satisfy navigation requirements of a variety of application including missiles, both fixed and rotary aircraft, UAV's, munitions, targets and drones. paper provides an introduction to the qq MIGITS systems, followed by a description qq system testing performed thus far.
